At the rcquest of the Parthians and Armenians, Pompey gave arbiters to settle their boundaries. Plutarch says that this was the main office of the Roman Feciales, not to allow recoursc to be had to arms till all hope of a peaceablc decision was gone. And Strabo says of the Druids of the Gauls, that formerly they were arbiters between hostile parties, and often made them part without fighting, who were drawn up in wal-like array against each other. The same writer testi- fies that the priests in Iberia had the same office.
